Recommend README LICENSE and .gitignore for all repositories
Yes — it's strongly recommended that every repository include a README, LICENSE, and .gitignore. Here's why:
Table
File	Purpose	Why It Matters
README.md	Project overview, setup instructions, usage guide	Helps others (and future you) understand what the project does and how to run it
LICENSE	Legal terms for use, modification, and distribution	Protects your work and tells others what they can and can't do with your code
.gitignore	Lists files/folders Git should ignore (e.g., node_modules/, .env, build files)	Keeps your repo clean, reduces clutter, and prevents accidentally committing sensitive data
Are they mandatory? No — GitHub won't stop you from creating a repo without them. But skipping them is considered poor practice, especially for public repositories.
Bottom line: These three files are the baseline for a professional, usable, and maintainable repository.
