All three professional repository files are ready for you. Here's what each one does:
📄 README.md
Your project's front page on GitHub. Includes features table, installation steps, usage guide, tech stack, browser support, your author info with social links, and contribution guidelines.
README.md
📄 LICENSE (MIT)
The MIT License is the gold standard for open-source projects. It lets anyone use, modify, and distribute your code freely — while keeping your copyright. It's permissive, professional, and widely trusted.
LICENSE
📄 .gitignore
Tells Git which files to ignore (like OS junk files, editor configs, logs, and build folders). Keeps your repo clean and prevents accidental commits of unnecessary files.
.gitignore
🚀 How to Add Them to Your Repo
Download all three files above
Place them in the same folder as your index.html
Run these commands:
bash
Copy
git add README.md LICENSE .gitignore
git commit -m "Add professional README, LICENSE, and .gitignore"
git push origin main
